<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911106-0029</DOCNO><DOCID>911106-0029.</DOCID><HL>   International:   BT Is Offering Discounts,   Bonuses to Share Buyers   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>11/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   BT</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)</IN><NS>STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LONDON -- Discounts and bonus shares will be offered totempt the share-buying public to take part in the latest saleof British Telecommunications PLC shares, the Britishgovernment said.   Those who register in advance with BT's share informationoffice can choose either a discount of around 8% onapplications for as many as 1,000 shares or a bonus share forevery 10 applied for up to a 1,500-share maximum.</LP><TEXT>   The government is selling about half its remaining 48%stake in the company to raise about #5 billion ($8.87billion). The incentives come on top of the discountindividual applicants already are being given on the pricepaid by large institutional investors. Incentives areavailable only to those who register before the closing datein mid-November.   The offer is scheduled to close in early December andfirst dealings will be some time around Dec. 9. It hasn'tbeen disclosed at what price the stock will be offered.   The 8% concession is worth about #30 on every 100 sharesallocated and retained until the relevant date.   Alternatively, applicants can opt for one bonus share forevery 10 held until Dec. 31, 1994. The maximum number ofbonus shares is 150.   BT recently posted an unexpected drop in earnings for itssecond quarter ended Sept. 30.</TEXT></DOC>